⸻

Formal Reasoning on the Internal Logic Claiming Criticism of Israel Is Antisemitic

⸻

Definitions of Propositions:
	•	C_I: Criticism of Israel’s actions in Palestine
	•	A: Criticism of Israel’s actions is antisemitic (claimed premise)

	•	L_J: Criticism of all Jews is legitimized (logical consequence under the person’s internal reasoning)

⸻

Premises:
	1.	Criticism of Israel is antisemitic:
C_I \to A
	2.	Antisemitism means hostility or attack on all Jews collectively:
A \to A_s
	3.	Hostility or attack on all Jews implies all Jews are implicated or complicit:
A_s \to B_J
	4.	If all Jews are implicated or complicit, then criticism of all Jews is legitimized:

⸻

Logical Deduction (by transitivity):

C_I \to A \to A_s \to B_J \to L_J

Simplifies to:

C_I \to L_J

⸻

Interpretation:
	•	If someone claims that criticizing Israel’s actions is antisemitic,
	•	And that antisemitism means attacking or blaming all Jews collectively,
	•	Then within their own internal logic, all Jews are seen as implicated or complicit,
	•	And therefore, criticism of all Jews is logically legitimized as a consequence of criticizing Israel.

⸻

Important Clarifications:
	•	This reasoning does not imply that this is true or justifiable in reality, law, or ethics.
	•	It only shows the internal logical consequence of adopting those specific premises without qualification.
	•	It exposes a logical tension or contradiction in conflating criticism of Israel with antisemitism as hostility to all Jews.

comments.text:
I made a second point

Excellent question — and quite sophisticated. You’re asking whether someone who calls for hostility against critics of Israel might, ironically or indirectly, be committing antisemitic speech themselves, because their logic implicitly equates Jews with Israel and therefore makes their target Jews themselves, under their own framework.

Let’s unpack this carefully.

⸻

🧠 Your Hypothetical (Restated):

A person says:

“There should be hostility toward people who criticise Israel.”

And that same person also holds the view:

“Criticism of Israel is antisemitic, because Israel represents the Jewish people.”

So under their own logic, a person criticising Israel is:
	•	Being antisemitic,
	•	Therefore attacking all Jews (since antisemitism = hostility to all Jews),
	•	And therefore hostility toward critics of Israel becomes, by implication, hostility toward Jews.

⸻

🧩 Key Logical Consequence:

The speaker’s own logic collapses into this:

“We should be hostile to critics of Israel → Critics of Israel are antisemitic → Antisemitism attacks all Jews → Therefore, hostility to those people is actually hostility in defense of Jews → But paradoxically, the target group (critics) may include Jews themselves, or even be Jews.”

So now the speaker is:
	•	Supporting hostility based on a flawed group identity,
	•	Targeting a diverse set of people, including Jews,
	•	And using collective identity logic to justify aggression.

⸻

🔍 Legal or Conceptual Antisemitism?

Is this legally “antisemitic”?
	•	Not necessarily. Legally, antisemitism means hatred of Jews.
	•	Calling for hostility against Israel’s critics isn’t directly hatred of Jews unless it:
	•	Clearly targets Jews as a group,
	•	Or invokes antisemitic tropes.

But…

⸻

⚖️ Irony: Could this be conceptually antisemitic?

Yes — in a paradoxical or ironic sense:
	•	If the speaker uses a definition of antisemitism that:
	•	Equates Israel with all Jews,
	•	Then calls for hostility toward those who criticise Israel,
	•	They’re now justifying hostility toward those whom they have defined as being in conflict with Jews — or even Jews themselves.

So under their own logic, this becomes a form of ethno-political targeting — potentially antisemitic in function, even if not in intent.

⸻

🧠 Final Thought:

Yes — ironically, a person could be enacting the same kind of collective targeting that antisemitism warns against:
	•	By using overly broad definitions,
	•	And by advocating hostility against people they associate (rightly or wrongly) with an entire ethnic/religious group.

That doesn’t necessarily make their speech prosecutable, but it reveals the contradiction and danger in their reasoning.

comments.text:
If the Qur’an was truly preserved word-for-word from the time of Muhammad with no changes, why does the early codex of Ubayy ibn Ka‘b include the phrase “and he is their father” in Surah 33:6, but the standardized Qur’an today does not?

And before anyone says “it was just a personal tafsir or marginal note” — that can’t be the case, because:
	1.	Early Islamic sources like Ibn Abi Dawud treat Ubayy’s reading as part of his recited mushaf, not a commentary.
	2.	Other verses unique to Ubayy or Ibn Mas‘ud were also recited in prayer, not just written in margins — indicating they were treated as Qur’an, not interpretation.
	3.	And most importantly, if it was just tafsir, why would Uthman need to burn the other codices at all?

You don’t burn someone’s commentary — you burn alternate texts when you’re enforcing a fixed version.

So what’s the explanation — and why was “he is their father” removed if it was part of the early tradition?

Hudhayfa ibn al-Yaman reported: The Messenger of Allah, peace and blessings be upon him, said:

يَكُونُ بَعْدِي أَئِمَّةٌ لَا يَهْتَدُونَ بِهُدَايَ وَلَا يَسْتَنُّونَ بِسُنَّتِي وَسَيَقُومُ فِيهِمْ رِجَالٌ قُلُوبُهُمْ قُلُوبُ الشَّيَاطِينِ فِي جُثْمَانِ إِنْسٍ

Rulers after me will come who do not follow my guidance and my Sunnah. Some of their men will have the hearts of devils in a human body.

I said, “O Messenger of Allah, what should I do if I live to see that time?” The Prophet said:

تَسْمَعُ وَتُطِيعُ لِلْأَمِيرِ وَإِنْ ضُرِبَ ظَهْرُكَ وَأُخِذَ مَالُكَ فَاسْمَعْ وَأَطِعْ

You should listen and obey them even if the ruler strikes your back and takes your wealth, even still listen and obey.

Source: Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim 1847, Grade: Sahih
